occurrences.line_text: In which when as she him anew had clad,
He gan t'efforce the euidence anew,
He gan deuize, to be aueng'd anew
Who therewith flesht, vpon him set anew,
Faire Angela (quoth she) men do her call,
Which long'd to Angela, the Saxon Queene,
Th'Angelicall soft trembling voyces made
Or Angell, th'authour of all woman kind;
To send thine Angell from her bowre of blis,
Angell, or Goddesse do I call thee right?
Nor Goddesse I, nor Angell, but the Mayd,
Like a sweet Angell twixt two clouds vphild:
She Angel-like, the heyre of ancient kings
And laid her stole aside. Her angels face
In heauenly throne, where thousand Angels shine?
The blessed Angels to and fro descend
And this bright Angels towre quite dims that towre of glas.
Like as it had bene many an Angels voice,
But heauenly pourtraict of bright Angels hew,
Like Angels life was then mens happy cace;
That blessed Angels, he sends to and fro,
With heauenly powre, and by Angels reskewd,
Such as the Angels weare before Gods tribunall.
Fit song of Angels caroled to bee;
Emongst the Angels, a whole legione
And bright, that seemed borne of Angels brood,
The heauenly pourtraict of bright Angels hew.
With that her angels face, vnseene afore,
But like to Angels playing heauenly toyes;
Who soone as he beheld that angels face,
Mongst which crept litle Angels through the glittering gleames.
Seemed those litle Angels did vphold
And the sharpe yron did for anger eat,
To fret for anger, or for griefe to mone?
Outrageous anger, and woe-working iarre,
But full of anger fiercely to him cride;
Emongst them was sterne Strife, and Anger stout,
But for the present did her anger shrowd;
That nought but dire reuenge his anger mote defray.
And strife, and warre, and anger does subdew:
They doe his anger calme, and cruell vengeance stay.
That she repented sore, to haue him angered.
But Phoebe therewith sore was angered,
Ne once to breath a while their angers tempest ceast.
Into the vtmost Angle of the world he knew.
And loue, themselues of her name Angles call.
And all that might his angrie passage stay,
Then tooke the angrie witch her golden cup,
Her angrie teame breaking their bonds of peace,
She threw away her burden angrily;
And snatching from her hand halfe angrily
His angry steede did chide his foming bitt,
And angry Ioue an hideous storme of raine
Threatning her angry sting, him to dismay:
Halfe angry asked him, for what he came.
Before that angry heauens list to lowre,
With pittie calmd, downe fell his angry mood.
Him litle answerd th'angry Elfin knight;
The angry beasts not rashly to despise,
Againe his wonted angry weapon proou'd:
The mortall sting his angry needle shot
Both knights and Ladies forth right angry far'd,
He wist himselfe amisse, and angry said;
But Guyons angry blade so fierce did play
And as a Beare whom angry curres haue touzd,
So is his angry courage fairely pacifyde.
But she with angry scorne him did withstond,
That with the angry working of the waue,
Before that angry Gods, and cruell skye
An angry Waspe th'one in a viall had
Fond Squire, full angry then sayd Paridell,
Throwne out by angry Ioue in his vengeance,
And fayned still her former angry mood,
To whom I cald aloud, halfe angry therewithall.
That he could make; And eeke that angry foole
To whom the Captaine in full angry wize
In secret anguish and vnpittied plaint,
And bitter anguish of his guiltie sight,
For anguish great they gan to rend their heare,
But pynd away in anguish and selfe-wild annoy.
But her deare heart with anguish did torment,
By this sad Vna fraught with anguish sore,
For to vnfold the anguish of your hart:
For wondrous anguish in his hart it wrought,
And hellish anguish did his soule assaile,
Or anguish in her hart, is hard to tell:
And prickt with anguish of his sinnes so sore,
For pitty of his paine and anguish sore;
Then full of griefe and anguish vehement,
Of anguish, rather then of crime hath beene,
The gnawing anguish and sharpe gelosy,
Whence forth it breakes in sighes and anguish rife,
In restlesse anguish and vnquiet paine:
And did consume his gall with anguish sore,
But through long anguish, and selfe-murdring thought
In wilfull anguish, and dead heauinesse,
His chaunge of cheere, that anguish did bewray,
Which stirs vp anguish and contentious rage:
The signes of anguish one mote plainely read,
And pyning anguish hid in gentle hart,
And adding anguish to the bitter wound,
Full of sad anguish, and in heauy case:
So much the greater still her anguish grew,
She parted thence, her anguish to appease.
And all the night for bitter anguish weepe,
The anguish of his paine to ouerpasse:
And there all night himselfe in anguish tost,
The bitter anguish of their sharpe disease,
Sorrow, and anguish, and impatient paine
That more increast the anguish of his paine.
His hart quite deaded was with anguish great,
As one with griefe and anguishe ouercum,
In wretched anguishe and incessant woe,
Seeking aduentures, where they anie knew.
And then stole fire from heauen, to animate
And to faire semblaunce doth light faith annexe;
His noble hart; thereto she did annexe
Therefore his house is vnto his annext;
That both their liues may likewise be annext
Forecasting, how his foe he might annoy,
But pynd away in anguish and selfe-wild annoy.
His deare delights were able to annoy:
That her sweet peace and pleasures did annoy,
All pleasaunce was to them griefe and annoy:
By Stygian lake I vow, whose sad annoy
To banish sloth, that oft doth noble mindes annoy.
Annoy this noble Knight, and sorely him constraine.
Which I expected long, now turnd to sad annoy?
Far from all neighbourhood, the which annoy it may.
My stubborne smart, but more annoyance breed,
Night thou foule Mother of annoyance sad,
That once their quiet gouernment annoyd,
Yet oft annoyd with sundry bordragings
For that wilde Bore, the which him once annoyd,
Whose too long absence him had sore annoyd,
And eke through heauie armes, which sore annoyd
(Then answerd he) which often hath annoyd
But most of all Defetto him annoyde,
The same so sore annoyed has the knight,
And sore annoyed, groping in that griesly night.
And glauncing fell to ground, but him annoyed naught.
So many monsters, which the world annoyed;
Eftsoones deuisd redresse for such annoyes;
But mucky filth his braunching armes annoyes,
For dread of whom, and for those Picts annoyes,
Such as the troubled Theaters oftimes annoyes.
In mighty armes he was yclad anon,
Of deadly drugs I gaue him drinke anon,
Fly therefore, fly this fearefull stead anon,
At bold Canutus; but of him was slaine anon.
And bad her all things put in readinesse anon.
Sate downe vpon the dusty ground anon,
Of that rockes fall, which euer and anon
Anon she gan perceiue the house to quake,
All vnawares he started vp anon,
Against him made againe. So both anon
That all which I put in, fals out anon;
Supposd to be. They do arriue anone,
Who passing by, forth led her guestes anone
And euer and anone with rosie red
For soone as maisterie comes, sweet loue anone
And euer and anone the rosy red,
Anone one sent out of the thicket neare
And euer and anone, when none was ware,
Vnto his lofty steede he clombe anone,
But walkt about them euer and anone,
To whom as he approcht, he knew anone,
There did the Prince him ouertake anone,
And lighting candles new, gan search anone,
And in another corner wide were strowne
To loue another. Lo then for thine ayd
And eke this battels end, will need another place.
Another like faire tree eke grew thereby,
Another said, that in his eyes did rest
Another said, he saw him moue his eyes indeed.
Vnto another loue, and to another land.
Vnto another loue, and to another land.
Another her out boastes, and all for tryall strips.
Another warre, and other weapons I
Another blis before mine eyes I place,
Another happinesse, another end.
Another happinesse, another end.
Him to entrap vnwares another way he wist.
Vnto another rowme, whose dore forthright,
Another did the dying bronds repaire
Another wretch, whose carkasse deepe was drent
They in another great round vessell plast,
Another seemed enuious, or coy,
Another in her teeth did gnaw a rush:
Another Damsell of that gentle crew,
Sir Guyon chaunst eke on another booke,
Then he another and another did expell.
Then he another and another did expell.
Till that he came vnto another gate,
But he him selfe betooke another way,
To chaunge my liefe, and loue another Dame,
Another arrow hath your louers hart to hit.
Another harnesse, which did hang thereby,
That heales vp one and makes another wound:
The like that mine, may be your paine another tide.
For at that berth another Babe she bore,
To make another like the former Dame,
Another Florimell, in shape and looke
Another knight, whom tempest thither brought,
Hath found another partner of your payne:
Another plant, that raught to wondrous hight,
Who from her went to seeke another lot,
Another yron dore, on which was writ,
That she your loue list loue another knight,
And loues another, with whom now she go'th
The other breathing now another spright,
And with her alwaies ride, till he another get.
Another like, that were like faire and bright,
So that the doome was to another day differd.
And after him another Knight, that hote
Shall for another canticle be spared.
Her second care, though in another kind;
Vntill another tyde, that I it finish may.
Selfe to forget to mind another, is ouersight.
I will deferre the end vntill another tide.
And then another, till that likewise fleet;
Comprised be, I will them in another tell.
But farre away from these, another sort
Both strongly arm'd, as fearing one another;
Which to another place I leaue to be perfected.
The which another did, who now is fled with shame.
Another that would seeme to haue more wit,
One while she blam'd her selfe; another whyle
That for another Canto will more fitly fall.
Soone after these he saw another Knight,
Againe the Pagan threw another dart,
Marcht with that mayd, fit matter for another song.
Another knight in his despiteous pryde;
So fare on foote till thou another gayne,
Turned his steede about another way,
That in another Canto shall to end be brought.
Was wandred in the wood another way,
The end whereof Ile keepe vntill another cast.
And drawing thence his speach another way,
Another while I baytes and nets display,
Another time, when as they did dispose
Another quest, another game in vew
Another quest, another game in vew
Another Damzell, as a precious gemme,
Thy Loue is there aduaunst to be another Grace.
And graced her so much to be another Grace.
Another Grace she well deserues to be,
Forgetfull of his owne, that mindes anothers cares.
Anothers wrongs to wreake vpon thy selfe:
Your court'sie takes on you anothers due offence.
Him ill beseemes, anothers fault to name,
That seekes to know anothers griefe in vaine,
Vpon your selues anothers wrong to wreake?
And in anothers losse great pleasure take,
But answer none receiues: the darknes him does shrowd.
Staid not to answer, scarcely did refraine,
Which answer when the groome returning, brought
Mylde answer made; he was an errant Knight,
Most answerable to his wyld disguize
But the rude wench her answer'd nought at all,
Him litle answerd th'angry Elfin knight;
Charmd or enchaunted (answerd he then ferce)
And Ecchoes three answerd it selfe againe:
Who answerd him full soft, he could not tell.
He answerd nought at all, but adding new
In great disdaine, he answerd; Hardy Elfe,
Who groning deepe, thus answerd him againe;
Who lifting vp his head, him answerd thus:
She answerd nought, but more abasht for shame,
The Dwarfe him answerd, Sir, ill mote I stay
And euery one her answerd, that too late
Her mildly answer'd; Beldame be not wroth
And with the like him answerd euermore:
But answerd, Sir him wise I neuer held,
He little answer'd, but in manly heart
She litle answer'd him, but lightly did aggrate.
Vnhappy mayd (then answerd she) whose dread
I cald, but no man answerd to my clame.
To whom she answerd, Then it is by name
And many things demaund, to which she answer'd light.
Thus answer'd; Lewdly thou my loue deprauest,
(Then answerd he) which often hath annoyd
To whom he answerd thus; My haplesse case
Yet answerd thus; Not vnto me the shame,
Yet boldly answer'd, as he rightly might;
They answer'd him, that no such beast they saw,
Surely my sonne (then answer'd he againe)
Not I so happy, answerd then that swaine,
To whom they answer'd, as did appertaine,
To ward the same, nor answere commers call.
But no man car'd to answere to his crye.
He could not tell: ne euer other answere made.
His answere likewise was, he could not tell.
To whom the Redcrosse knight this answere sent,
Wherewith reviu'd, this answere forth he threw;
Whose simple answere, wanting colours faire
Whereto that single knight did answere frame;
To speake a while, ne ready answere make,
Or answere for thy wrong, as shall fall out in fight.
And gan this bitter answere to him make;
That seemeth well to answere to your weede?
With proud disdaine did scornefull answere make;
Both which to barre, he with this answere met her;
Yet mote he algates now abide, and answere make.
Ne ought to answere thereunto did find;
Yet for the time this answere he to him behight.
But she thereto nould plead, nor answere ought
One word durst speake, or answere him a whit thereto.
Made answere, that the Mayd of whom they spake,
He answered nought, but in a traunce still lay,
He could not tell, againe he answered.
Palmer, (him answered the Redcrosse knight)
Yet mildly him to purpose answered;
Him Mammon answered; That goodly one,
To whom the Palmer fearelesse answered;
Him answered, as courtesie became,
Him answered; Faire sonne, be no whit sad
Who gently answered, They entrance did desire.
It answered was, her name was Prays-desire,
In his big base them fitly answered,
The gentle warbling wind low answered to all.
At last the passion past she thus him answered.
Her shortly answered; Faire martiall Mayd
To whom halfe weeping, she thus answered,
With nought but ghastly lookes him answered,
Him answered, that all were now retyrd
It to reueale: who still her answered, there was nought.
Then answered the righteous Artegall,
He answered, that he would try it streight,
But when he heard her answeres loth, he knew
And hearing th'answeres of his pregnant wit,
Who thereto answering, said; the tydings bad,
And answering their wearie turnes around,
But neede, that answers not to all requests,
The Antelope, and Wolfe both fierce and fell;
Wayting when as the Antheme should be sung on hye.
With curious antickes, and full faire aumayld:
Wouen with antickes and wild Imagery:
Wrought with wilde Antickes, which their follies playd,
With salue, or antidote, or other mene
And proud Antiochus, the which aduaunst
In Satyres shape Antiopa he snatcht:
The antique rolles, which there lye hidden still,
The antique ruines of the Romaines fall:
Not that great Champion of the antique world,
Arayd in antique robes downe to the ground,
For th'antique world excesse and pride did hate;
That all this famous antique history,
And in this antique Image thy great auncestry.
It was an auncient worke of antique fame,
The antique shapes of kings and kesars straunge & rare.
The antique world, in his first flowring youth,
And leaue the rudenesse of that antique age
Not that, which antique Cadmus whylome built
And antique Registers for to auise,
In antique times was saluage wildernesse,
The noble braunch from th'antique stocke was torne
Whom antique history so high doth raise,
And antique praises vnto present persons fit.
O goodly vsage of those antique times,
As whilome was the antique worldes guize,
But by record of antique times I find,
And all his armour seem'd of antique mould,
Of those same antique Peres, the heauens brood,
The royall seed, the antique Troian blood,
Where is the Antique glory now become,
As it in antique bookes is mentioned.
That of the antique Troian stocke, there grew
That all the antique Worthies merits far did passe.
There was the signe of antique Babylon,
Whylome as antique stories tellen vs,
After the Persian Monarks antique guize,
But antique age yet in the infancie
That whilome were (as antique fathers tell)
Therefore the antique wisards well inuented,
The image of the antique world compare,
But to the antique vse, which was of yore,
Well therefore did the antique world inuent,
That hight Antiquitie of Faerie lond.
And wonder of antiquitie long stopt his speach.
Well did Antiquitie a God thee deeme,
The warlike Worthies, from antiquitie,
And records of antiquitie appeare,
Yet being matcht with plaine Antiquitie,
But vouch antiquities, which no body can know.
So long they red in those antiquities,
Therefore a God him sage Antiquity
But where shall I in all Antiquity
High Cï¿½sar, great Pompey, and fierce Antonius.
And so did warlike Antony neglect
Not perceable with power of any starre:
Where plaine none might her see, nor she see any plaine.
Ne euer would to any by-way bend,
And thrise three times did fast from any bit:
For she was wondrous faire, as any liuing wight.
Or if that any else did Ioue excell:
Vnfit he was for any worldy thing,
For death it was, when any good he saw,
And him no lesse, that any like did vse,
For doubtlesse death ensewd, if any him descryde.
And there abode, whilst any beast of name
That it would pitty any liuing eie.
No magicke arts hereof had any might,
And chauft, that any on his backe should sit;
Yet neuer any could that girlond win,
Each dore he opened without any breach;
That any wound could heale incontinent:
If any strength we haue, it is to ill,
Here in this place, or any other wight,
And left not any marke, where it did light;
Ne yet hath any knight his courage crackt.
Her feeble pulse, to proue if any drop
Ne lets her waues with any filth be dyde,
Ne any euill meanes she did forbeare,
Yet was there not with her else any one,
And she more sweet, then any bird on bough,
The least of which was match for any knight.
So long as any thing it in the caudron got.
Liues any, that you hath thus ill apaid?
Disguised slaine, ere any thereof thought:
That neuer entrance any durst pretend,
Are not firme land, nor any certein wonne,
Ne made for shipping any certaine port,
Their dainty parts from vew of any, which them eyde.
If pourtrayd it might be by any liuing art.
That neuer any mote with her compaire.
She softly felt, if any member mooued,
If any puffe of breath, or signe of sence she fand.
Ne any noise she made, ne word she spake,
Where so he heares, that any doth confound
Not that she lusted after any one;
And if that any drop of slombring rest
Ne brauer proofe in any, of thy powre
But dare thou not, I charge, in any cace,
The feends do quake, when any him to them does name.
And to him said, If any leaches skill,
Was neuer so great wast in any place,
Whose Empire lenger here, then euer any stood.
But gentle Sleepe enuyde him any rest;
As any Nymph (let not it be enuyde,)
If any tract of him or tydings they mote trace.
Each bird his mate, ne any does enuie
Nor Aeolus sharp blast could worke them any wrong.
Or ply him selfe to any honest trade,
And slew him cruelly, ere any reskew came.
Ne any may that Monster match in fight,
I glad by any meanes her grace to gaine,
Safe her, I neuer any woman found,
Then any should of falsenesse her reproue,
That is the cause, why neuer any knight
Of knights and ladies any meetings were,
And tell thy griefe, if any hidden lye;
For he was long, and swift as any Roe,
This fire be quencht by any wit or might,
Ne yet by any meanes remou'd away,
By any ridling skill, or commune wit.
Such is thy wont, that still when any Knight
Ne any dar'd their perill to partake;
Not farre away, not meete for any guest
And if by fortune any litle nap
What medicine can any Leaches art
For any knight, vpon a ventrous knight
A downe in vaine, ne harm'd her any more.
By any Ladies side for Leman to haue laine.
Or any of the Thracian Nimphes in saluage chase.
That any little blow on her did light,
And wisht it were in her to doe him any grace.
Ne any but your selfe, O dearest dred,
That any bud thereof doth scarse remaine,
She were as faire as any vnder skie.
Nor hart could wish for any queint deuice,
Ne euer for rebuke or blame of any balkt.
Nor any blemish, which the worke mote blame;
Ye Gods of seas, if any Gods at all
Ne could by search nor any meanes out find
Nor vnto any meaner to complaine,
And if then those may any worse be red,
Ne any liu'd on ground, that durst withstand
Ne any armour could his dint out ward,
For any thing wold slacke, but still vppon him hong.
And durst the depth of any water sownd.
Nor memory thereof to any nation.
Ne euer any asketh reason why.
Ne any may his mighty will withstand;
Ne any may his soueraine power shonne,
Ne any of them durst come in his way,
Ne any Knight was absent, that braue courage bore.
Ne any token doth thereof abide:
By any skill or labour it would sit,
Eftsoones he stood as still as any stake,
For any death to chaunge life though most bad:
Not wronging any other by my will,
Any her proud obseruaunce will withstand,
To which if thou canst win him any way,
Ne yet to any other wight on ground,
Ne would be taught with any termes, to lerne
Least any should betray his Lady treacherously.
Least any more such practise should proceede.
Nor sire, nor sonnes, nor any could she spie:
Serues her, as any Princesse vnder sky,
